<br>
This isn't true.  Its also surprising, even to me, when I started parsing myself heavily.<br>
<br>
I'm 65, with SoS and about 70 AAs, in a reasonably powerful guild -- Pre VT/Tier3+ PoP, but still in the top 7-10 guilds on the server.  Magelo = 470000.  I'm not terribly uber by any means.  I expect elemental wizards are dealing as much as 50% more than me sustainable.<br>
<br>
I expected 110 dps sustained average.<br>
However, my dps average for 35 hours of hunting, was 197.23 dps.<br>
<br>
This is unskewed dps.  For those of you who know parses know that you can't parse non-melee effectively becuase of casting times.  So I got around this by using the main tank's uptime as my timer, rather than my timer.  Thus, if the MT was attacking, it counted against my total DPS.<br>
<br>
I'd like to point out that I never hunt with warrior MTs unless desperate.<br>
<br>
The secret to this dps is a combination of things.  The first is a mana robe (not listed on my magelo because its guild property).  I work toward 100% mana robe uptime.  This means whenever I'm not casting a nuke, a harvest, or my epic (only at the end of every fight, I often eat through it and keep eating).  This means that even when my buttons are repopping, I'm mana-robing.<br>
<br>
The second thing, and probably the most obvious, is a horse.  If you dont' own a horse as a 60+ wizard, quit the game now.  <br>
<br>
The final thing is more of an idea.  The idea is what I call &quot;Deep Pockets.&quot;  Some people say that mana pool means nothing, but in reality, it does.  On average, someone in a group takes a break, or a pull takes more time than normal, at least once per 15 minutes.  This is not time for you to take a break, its time for you to chain mana robe, which allows huge regen.  Your mana pool allows you to maintain good dps even though you are beating your regen for a majority of the time.<br>
<br>
197 is huge,when compared to people in my own tier and above (including elemental geard non-wizards).  Rogues tend to average 130dps.  Monks average 150ish.  Rangers with EQ/AM3 average 170 if they are really trying, 180ish with an elemental bow.  Mages are about 150-170, depending on AAs.<br>
<br>
And no one else comes close.<br>
<br>
Wizards are the overall top DPS dealer in any average group situation (without a warrior as MT).<br>
<br>
Varressa Evocara &lt;Final Destiny&gt;<br>
65 Arcanist, Ayonae Ro. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=artillis>Artillis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Enjoys Sheep Erotica</span><br>  Posts: 1973<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/21/03 3:28 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How much of a dps ...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Wizards are the overall top DPS dealer in any average group situation (without a warrior as MT).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
